mselves and in combination, can facilitate or impede patient safety. Individual factors include safety-relevant knowledge, skills, abilities, and personality traits such as conscientiousness and emotional stability. Team factors include group communication, training, and leadership. Finally, organizational factors include the safety culture and climate. Throughout the book, different evidence-based intervention programs are described that can help practitioners promote patient safety and prevent accidents. The book is a valuable resource for both researchers and practitioners interested in understanding, maintaining, and improving patient safety in a variety of applied settings. It is based on the most up-to-date research evidence from psychology and neighboring disciplines, and it is written in a clear and non-technical language understandable for a wide audience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMedical carexSafety measures. 0aMedical errorsxPrevention. 0aPatientsxSafety measures. 4aAccidents. 4aPsychology. 4aSafety Climate. 4aSafety. 4aTraining. 7aMEDICAL / Clinical Medicine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Medicine and Life Sciences 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023849508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Medicine and Life Sciences 2000 - 2014z9783110637915oZDB-23-GML08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine 2014z9783110370379oZDB-23-DPM0 cprintz978311028173640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311028192740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110281927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com